or civic benefits. The Right to Be Counted examines how Delhi's urban poor, in an effort to gain visibility from the local state, incrementally stake their claims to a house and life in the city. Contributing to debates about the contradictions of state governmentality and the citizenship projects of the poor in Delhi, this book explores social suffering, logistics, and the logic of political mobilizations that emanate from processes of displacement and resettlement. Sanjeev Routray draws upon fieldwork conducted in various low-income neighborhoods throughout the 2010s to describe the process of claims-making as an attempt by the political community of the poor to assert its existence and numerical strength, and demonstrates how this struggle to be counted constitutes the systematic, protracted, and incremental political process by which the poor claim their substantive entitlements and become entrenched in the city. Analyzing various social, political, and economic relationships, as well as kinship networks and solidarity linkages across the political and social spectrum, this book traces the ways the poor work to gain a foothold in Delhi and establish agency for themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCitizenshipzIndiazDelhi. 0aCity planningzIndiazDelhi. 0aLand settlementxPolitical aspectszIndiazDelhi. 0aPoorxCivil rightszIndiazDelhi. 0aPoorxPolitical activityzIndiazDelhi. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  aCalculative Governmentality.  aDelhi.  aDisplacement and Resettlement.  aDocuments.  aHome.  aLaw and Resistance.  aMediation.  aNumerical Citizenship.  aTactics and Counter-tactics of Urban Poor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363214140